<br>
2 that should have plenty of oomph without STRONG controversy:<br>
<br>
1. In  the relationship of man and God (gods), Is a persons actions Predestined or Free Will. A varient could be are we genetically programed to act a certain way or is it environmental influences that determined our actions.<br>
<br>
2. Is the world flat or round? Check out the flat world society. <br>
<br>
Most important things to remember!!!! <br>
<br>
1. At the beginning of your argument, define it. You must at the opening of your argument clearly state  what you are arguing (debating), then state the Pro stance, then the Con stance.<br>
<br>
That will limit your argument to only two positions and doesn't allow for tangents or blurring the issue.<br>
<br>
2. Facts are only an arguing tool. It is the strentgh of your argument that counts.They in  themselves don't determine whether you have effectively argued your side. the goal of the essay is more about did you LOGICALLY and in an effective manner lay out your reasons.<br>
<br>
3. There is no such thing as right or wrong when it comes to argumentative debate. In a matter of fact, you can definitely score higher points with your Prof if you take something that is considered a fact and then effectively argue against it. (See the Flat World reference or Santa Clause)<br>
